BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR
Use the method of cylindrical shells to find the volume generated by rotating the region bounded by \(y=e^{-x^2},\) \(y=0,\) \(x=0,\) and \(x=1\) about the \(y\)-axis.

$PAR
Volume = \{ans_rule(30)\}

END_TEXT

ANS(num_cmp("pi*(1-1/exp(1))"));

$r = 1.5;
$l = -1.5;
$t = 1.5;
$bot = -0.5;
$yh=exp(-0.5**2);

$gr = init_graph($l,$bot, $r,$t, axes=>[0,0], size=>[250,250]);
add_functions( $gr,
	       "exp(-x^2) for x in <$l,$r> using color:blue and weight:2" );
$gr->moveTo(1, exp(-1));
$gr->lineTo(1, 0, 'blue', 2 );
$gr->moveTo(1, 0);
$gr->lineTo(0, 0, 'blue', 2 );
$gr->moveTo(0, 0);
$gr->lineTo(0, 1, 'blue', 2 );
$gr->new_color( 'ltblue', 214, 230, 244 );
$gr->fillRegion( [0.1, 0.6, 'ltblue'] );
$gr->moveTo(0.5,$yh);
$gr->lineTo(0.5, 0, 'black', 1,'dashed' );
$gr->lb( new Label(0.6, 0.35,'h',
    'black','left','center'));
$gr->moveTo(0,0.5);
$gr->lineTo(0.5, 0.5, 'black', 1,'dashed' );
$gr->lb( new Label(0.25,0.47,'x',
    'black','left','center'));
#$gr->lb( new Label(2.4,0.4,$a,
#    'black','right','center'));
$gr->moveTo(1,$bot);
$gr->lineTo(1, $t, 'black', 1,'dashed' );
$gr->lb( new Label(1.2,0.4,'x=',
    'black','right','center'));
$gr->lb( new Label(1.4,0.4,1,
    'black','right','center'));


BEGIN_SOLUTION
$PAR SOLUTION $PAR
The region to be rotated about the  \(y\)-axis is shown below. 
$BCENTER
\{image(insertGraph($gr),width=>250,height=>250,tex_size=>250)\}
$ECENTER $PAR
The region 
is rotated around the \(y\)-axis, so we have thin vertical cylindrical shells,  of thickness \(dx\).  
The interval needed by \(x\) to fill the region bounded by the curves is \(0 \leq x \leq 1\). 
$BR

For the integrand, we think of a cylindrical shell at \(x\) with height \(h = e^{-x^2} \), thickness \(dx\), rotated around the line \(x=0\) and so has circumference \(2\pi r = 2\pi x\). 
The volume then is
\[ 
V  = {\displaystyle\int}_{0}^{1} 2\pi x e^{-x^2} dx \]
We perform the substitution \( u = -x^2, \, du = -2x \, dx \). We also change the limits of
integration:$BR
\( x =0 \Rightarrow u=0 \) $BR
\( x =1 \Rightarrow u=-1 \) $BR
We then have
\[
 V =  - \pi {\displaystyle\int}_{0}^{-1}  e^{u} \, du 
  =  \pi   \Big[ e^u \Big]_{-1}^{0}  
=  \pi (1-e^{-1} )
\]

END_SOLUTION

